    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The inventory turnover ratio is a measure of how many times a company sells and replaces its inventory during a period. It is calculated by dividing the Cost of Goods Sold (COGS) by the Average Inventory.\n\nA low ratio means your boutique is moving stock slowly, which is a sign of a **slow-moving inventory** that is sitting on the shelves like a pile of uncut, unshaped clay waiting to be molded into a useful shape.\n\nIf your ratio is low, it means you are holding onto too much stuff that isn't selling. This is a classic **goblin problem**: you have a massive pile of goblin gold (inventory) that is not being spent on new goblin gold (sales).\n\nIn a clothing boutique, this could mean you have a huge pile of winter coats that are sitting in the back room, or perhaps you are overstocking on trendy items that are just not selling.\n\nTo fix this, you might need to **goblin-ify your pricing** (make it more attractive to the market) or **goblin-ify your marketing** (get more people to see your goblin gold).\n\nIf you want to know exactly how to calculate it, you need to know your CO",
